\begin_layout Section*
Spherical k-means clustering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Spherical k-means clustering the same idea, but with points on a sphere.
 We investigated a MATLAB implementation by Nguyen
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nguyen2008gene,nguyen_spherical_clustering"

\end_inset

, which required a mean-and-norm-normalized dataset located on a hypersphere.
 Important aspects of this implementation include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When there exists an empty cluster, the largest cluster is split
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use the dot product as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

negative distance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which leverages the fact that observations are unit vectors on the hypersphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use the normalized sum of observations as a centroid/mean, which leverages
 the fact that observations are unit vectors on the hypersphere.
 Note that this fails on pathological cases where the sum of observations
 is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Our investigation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to test how well the spherical k-means clustering algorithm worked,
 we constructed a random data set using the Von Mises distribution random
 sampling function from the MATLAB Circular Statistics Toolbox
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "circstats"

\end_inset

.
 We constructed 70 clusters of 10 points each, using random points on the
 sphere as means and with 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=100$
\end_inset

, and then applied the spherical k-means clustering and visualized the results
 on the unit three dimensional sphere, color coded for each cluster and
 with estimated means labeled as red 
